                            <body>
                                <p> NAIROBI, Sept 23 (Reuters) - Sudanese rebels accused the  government on Monday of widespread bombing of civilian targets  in the south, saying more than 20 people had been killed in  aerial attacks over the past week.</p>
                                <p> The Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) said Khartoum had  targeted a church, market place, villages and refugee camps  using newly purchased Russian MiG-29 bombers.</p>
                                <p> There was no immediate comment from the government.  Swiss-based Christian Solidarity International confirmed in a  statement that several villages in Twic county, northern Bahr el  Ghazal, had been bombarded on Friday and Saturday, killing at  least five people including two boys aged three and 13.</p>
                                <p> "These attacks are absolutely unjustified, since they are on  non-military targets," SPLA spokesman Samson Kwaje said in a  statement. "The targeted areas are IDP (internally displaced  people) camps, simple villages, cattle camps, churches and  market places.</p>
                                <p> "The blanket aerial bombardment of civil infrastructure, in  our view, is also meant to further complicate the peace  process...The regime should come to the peace talks at Machakos  (in Kenya) so that a ceasefire can be negotiated, after a  comprehensive resolution of the conflict is achieved."</p>
                                <p> The government in northern Sudan walked out of peace talks  -- widely seen as the best chance yet for ending 19 years of war  between the government and the SPLA -- earlier this month after  the rebels seized the strategic town of Torit.</p>
                                <p> Broadly the war pits the rebels, fighting for more autonomy  in the mainly animist and Christian south from the largely  Muslim, Arabised north.</p>
                                <p> There have been several reports of heavy fighting since the  peace talks broke down.</p>
                                <p> Kwaje said 17 people were killed in an attack on a camp in  Western Equatoria province on Saturday, along with 200 cattle.  On the same day, at least four people were killed in Twic  county, he said.</p>
                                <p> He said an Antonov plane dropped 14 bombs in Abyei on  Friday, killing a family while they slept. And on Thursday, five  villages around Bor town were also hit, hurting several people.</p>
                                <p> Khartoum has said it will not return to the negotiating  table until the SPLA has signed a ceasefire, while the SPLA has  maintained its stance that it will not cease fire until all  other issues are resolved.</p>
                                <p> Analysts say pressure from observers, especially the United  States, and war fatigue on both sides are likely to bring about  an eventual resumption of talks to end a civil war that has  killed two million people since 1983.</p>
                                <p> But they say the interruption to talks is dangerous and have  urged mediators to use forceful diplomacy to get the  negotiations back on track.    </p>
